Predicting NBA Regular Season Records To Find Undervalued or Overvalued Playoff Teams

</br>

by Akhil Chamarthy, Pranav Jayaraman, Anirudh Vadrevu, and Henry Vuong

An investigation on how regular season NBA statistics can be used to create an expected wins model that can then be used to determine if a team over performed or underperformed their expected win column.

Table of Contents¶

1. Exploratory Analysis of Data¶

2. Darwin Supervised Learning¶

3. Conclusion¶

Exploratory Analysis of Data¶

To analyze this problem, we decided to use regular season NBA data from the past 10 years. We scraped this data from the official NBA website (https://stats.nba.com/teams/), and added several of our own columns as well. The official NBA data had dozens of categories, including Traditional, Advanced, Four Factors, Misc, Scoring, Opponent, and Defense; each of these categories contained different pieces of data. For example, true shooting percentage (a statistic that measures how efficiently a player shot the ball) fell under Advanced, but field goal percentage (the number of shots made over the number of shots taken) fell under Traditional.

Our feature engineered columns were number players who received NBA awards during that season. These awards are given to top players at their position as voted by fans, media, and coaches. The features we created were:

  • Number of All Star players
  • Number of All-NBA 1st team players
  • Number of All-NBA 2nd team players
  • Number of All-NBA 3rd team players

Before running Darwin, we decided to explore our full dataset and its features.

Exploring the data gave our team a better understanding of some of the analytical statistics that the NBA uses in todays day and age, and disproved some of our long-held assumptions, such as the importance of defense for winning games. After finishing up our exploratory analysis, we were ready to move on to using Darwin with our dataset.

Darwin Supervised Learning¶

Darwin Model v1.0¶

We will now build a model using Darwin's Supervised Learning model that will use the wins percentage column as our label.
Our labels are NBA teams regular season records binned as so:

Label Win Percentage Range Win Range
0 >.65 >61.5 wins
1 .55-.65 45.1-53.3 wins
2 .45-.55 36.9-45.1 wins
3 .35-.45 <36.9 wins
4 <.35 <28.7 wins

Exclusive then inclusive for win ranges

Here are screenshots of our first model that we ran using all 92 features of our datset

The 10 most important features of our initial model.

The precision and recall of the training model.

The precision and recall of the testing model.

Initially, we fed Darwin our entire dataset. We thought that Darwin would normalize and scale our data, and would also perform feature selection and use the most important features to create the best model. However, we ran models using this method approx. ~50 times while fine tuning parameters, but were frustrated when the accuracy of our models failed to improve. We realized that Darwin may not have been performing feature selection and was overfitting our training data, so we decided to use the most important features from this model, which used every feature, and run another model with only these features included.

Darwin Model v2.0¶

The section below illustrates the steps to setup the Darwin environment, upload our datsets, clean the datsets, create our model, and test our model.

There were a total of eight teams total that over/under performed expectation, four of those teams being playoff contenders. The Denver Nuggets, LA Clippers, and Houston Rockets won more games than expected and the Utah Jazz won less games than expected.

Therefore, one might assume that the series between the Rockets and Jazz (currently going on at the time of this paper, with the Rockets leading 3-1) would be closer than expected. However, the Rockets lead the Jazz 3-1 in the series. Although the Rockets won more games than expected, they are still a very good team (this roster did make the Western Conference Finals last year and take the champion Warriors to 7 games), and so maybe an undervalued Rockets team is still an incredibly talented roster. The Denver Nuggets are currently playing the San Antonio Spurs, and as a 2-seed the Nuggets are heavily favored. But our model shows the Nuggets are overvalued, and the series is currently tied at 2 games each. Our predictions are currently a mixed bag, with some being more accurate than others, but given more data, we are sure our model will be more accurate.
